<subSubSection lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="376" pageId="24" pageNumber="375" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1127,1442,1592]" pageId="24" pageNumber="375">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,262,1442,1465]" pageId="24" pageNumber="375">Remarks.</emphasis>
According to the label data the specimen was studied by J. Weise who recognized it as a new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1905" box="[385,489,1474,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Solenispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[385,489,1474,1497]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="375">Solenispa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, he did not publish the description and 
<bibRefCitation author="PIC M." box="[1015,1127,1474,1497]" pageId="24" pageNumber="375" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref20214" refString="PIC M. 1923: Nouveautes diverses. Melanges Exotico-Entomologiques 38: 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1923">PIC (1923)</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1127,1442,1592]" pageId="24" pageNumber="375">
<superScript attach="left" box="[159,165,1519,1530]" fontSize="5" pageId="24" pageNumber="375">1</superScript>
This refers to the 
<specimenCount box="[319,449,1520,1539]" pageId="24" pageNumber="375" type="generic" typeStatus="paratypes">three paratypes</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Staines, 1996" authorityName="Staines" authorityYear="1996" box="[476,680,1520,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanea">
<emphasis box="[476,560,1520,1539]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="375">X. cyanea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="STAINES C. L." box="[565,680,1520,1539]" pageId="24" pageNumber="375" pagination="1 - 73" refId="ref20356" refString="STAINES C. L. 1996: The genus Cephaloleia (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae) in Central America and the West Indies. Revista de Biologia Tropical, Special Publication 3: 1 - 73 + 14 pls." type="journal article" year="1996">Staines, 1996</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Caracas, one of which was figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="STAINES C. L." pageId="24" pageNumber="375" pagination="1 - 73" refId="ref20356" refString="STAINES C. L. 1996: The genus Cephaloleia (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae) in Central America and the West Indies. Revista de Biologia Tropical, Special Publication 3: 1 - 73 + 14 pls." type="journal article" year="1996">STAINES (1996)</bibRefCitation>
. They possibly belong to a new species, however, all three have broken and missing antennae therefore I rather avoid describing this taxon until I have better preserved specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[113,1089,220,531]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">
validated the name by very short and uninformative description, which is written in singular and Pic gave only a single length measurement suggesting that he had only a single specimen at his disposal. Afterward it was listed only in catalogues (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="UHMANN E." box="[781,945,284,307]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" pagination="1 - 153" refId="ref20731" refString="UHMANN E. 1957 a: Chrysomelidae: Hispinae. Hispinae Americanae. In: HINCKS W. D. (ed.): Coleopterorum Catalogus Supplementa, Pars 35, Fasc. 1. Dr. W. Junk, 's-Gravenhage, vii + pp. 1 - 153." type="book chapter" year="1957">UHMANN 1957a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="UHMANN E." box="[956,1014,284,307]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" pagination="399 - 490" refId="ref20824" refString="UHMANN E. 1964: Chrysomelidae: Hispinae. Corrigenda et Addenda. In: STEEL W. O. (ed.): Coleopterorum Catalogus Supplementa. Pars 35. Fasc. 3. W. Junk, 's-Gravenhage, v + pp. 399 - 490." type="book chapter" year="1964">1964</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[113,1089,220,531]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">
I have studied the 
<typeStatus box="[338,431,316,339]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">holotype</typeStatus>
and in my opinion it belongs to the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1910" box="[884,997,316,339]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hybosispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[884,997,316,339]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">Hybosispa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it has typical shape of that genus and abdominal ventrites are not pubescent, while all known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1905" box="[140,241,380,403]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Solenispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[140,241,380,403]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">Solenispa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have them densely pubescent. Therefore I hereby transfer 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1923" box="[835,943,380,403]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Solenispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claripes">
<emphasis box="[835,943,380,403]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">S. claripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1910" box="[972,1082,380,403]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hybosispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[972,1082,380,403]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">Hybosispa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[113,1089,220,531]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">
It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Uhmann, 1939" authorityName="Uhmann" authorityYear="1939" box="[354,612,412,435]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hybosispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">
<emphasis box="[354,448,412,435]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">H. nitida</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="UHMANN E." box="[455,612,412,435]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" pagination="151 - 156" refId="ref20641" refString="UHMANN E. 1939: Hispinen des Deutschen Entomologischen Instituts, Berlin-Dahlem. III. Teil. (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae). 82. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Hispinen. Arbeiten uber Morphologische und Taxonomische Entomologie aus Berlin-Dahlem 6: 151 - 156." type="journal article" year="1939">Uhmann, 1939</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Uhmann, 1940" authorityName="Uhmann" authorityYear="1940" box="[663,968,412,436]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hybosispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufiventris">
<emphasis box="[663,805,412,436]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">H. rufiventris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="UHMANN E." box="[811,968,412,435]" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" pagination="113 - 120" refId="ref20686" refString="UHMANN E. 1940: Hispinen des Deutschen Entomologischen Instituts, Berlin-Dahlem. IV. Teil. (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae). 89. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Hispinen. Arbeiten uber Morphologische und Taxonomische Entomologie aus Berlin-Dahlem 7: 113 - 120." type="journal article" year="1940">Uhmann, 1940</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as all three share uniformly black dorsum. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1923" box="[568,689,444,467]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Solenispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claripes">
<emphasis box="[568,689,444,467]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="376">H. claripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in more impressed frons and vertex and pale coloured legs.
</paragraph>
